CHAPTER 1: Introduction — The Puzzle of Unequal Childlessness
Purpose: Establish the empirical puzzle, theoretical stakes, and the dissertation's contribution.
1.1 The Rise of Childlessness as a Stratified Phenomenon
Open with the empirical paradox: aggregate U.S. childlessness is rising, but the trend is profoundly unequal. Among women aged 40–49, childlessness rates range from 5.5% for those without a high school diploma to 27.4% for those with graduate degrees — and from 12% for foreign-born Hispanic women to 26% for native-born women in the Other racial category. This is not one story; it is many stories running simultaneously.
1.2 The Immigration Blind Spot in Fertility Research
Mainstream demographic accounts of childlessness focus on education, income, and marriage postponement. What they routinely miss: the compositional role of immigration. When roughly 39% of Hispanic women of reproductive age are foreign-born, any aggregate measure of "Hispanic fertility" is a weighted average of two very different populations. The failure to account for this has led to systematic misunderstanding of racial fertility differentials.
1.3 The Argument in Brief
This dissertation argues that the racial gradient in completed childlessness in the United States is substantially — though not entirely — an artifact of nativity composition, and that this compositional effect operates through two observable pathways: marriage and religious affiliation. It further argues that the financial dimensions of childlessness (studied in Chapters 2 and 3) and the nativity dimensions (studied in Chapter 4) are complementary, not competing, explanations — and that understanding childlessness requires both.
1.4 Theoretical Contributions

Bridging the fertility transition and immigrant incorporation literatures
Testing classic assimilation theory against segmented assimilation (Portes & Zhou, 1993)
Introducing the mediation framework for nativity-fertility relationships

1.5 Dissertation Roadmap
