CHAPTER 4: The Balance Sheet of Childlessness — Financial Structure and Family Formation
Purpose: Paper 2. Show that it is the composition of the household balance sheet, not aggregate income, that distinguishes childless from parent households.
4.1 Introduction: Beyond Income
The conventional economic account of childlessness focuses on income and opportunity costs. This chapter argues for a more granular view: what a household owns (retirement assets), what it owes (credit card debt), and whether it can access credit independently shape childlessness.
4.2 Data and Methods

2022 Survey of Consumer Finances (SCF)
Outcome: co-resident childlessness (ages 31–44); measurement limitations addressed
Logistic regression with Lasso-selected financial predictors
Survey weighting, multiple imputation

4.3 Results
4.3.1 The Retirement Asset Finding
OR = 1.05 per unit of retirement assets: the opportunity cost hypothesis confirmed
4.3.2 Credit Denial as a Barrier
OR = 2.01: credit-constrained households are more likely to be childless; parallel to Chapter 3's credit denial finding
4.3.3 The Income Null
Aggregate income and net worth are non-significant; only earned wages matter
4.3.4 The Race Mediation
Racial differences in co-resident childlessness are fully absorbed by financial and demographic controls, motivating the Chapter 5 test of the nativity hypothesis
4.4 Discussion

Two mechanisms by which financial structure shapes childlessness: opportunity cost (retirement assets) and material constraint (credit denial)
The bridge to Chapter 5: if race is fully mediated by financial/demographic controls, is nativity the underlying driver?


CHAPTER 5: Born Here or There — Nativity, Immigration, and Completed Childlessness
Purpose: Paper 3 (the NSFG analysis). Direct test of the nativity hypothesis using biological fertility, nativity data, and a sequential regression design.
5.1 Introduction: The Nativity Hypothesis
What the SCF analyses could not test; why the NSFG enables the test; the theoretical stakes
5.2 Data and Methods

2022–2023 NSFG female respondent file
Sample: women aged 40–49 (completed fertility); N = 1,490
Outcome: PARITY == 0 (children ever born); biological fertility, not co-resident status
Sequential logistic regression: Models 1–3
Post-treatment bias analysis
Five-level education coding (HIEDUC corrected for 2022–2023 wave)

5.3 Results
5.3.1 Descriptive: The Nativity Gap Within Race
Native-born Hispanic (22.6%) vs. foreign-born Hispanic (12.0%); native-born Other (25.8%) vs. foreign-born Other (11.8%); the convergence of native-born Hispanic and White women
5.3.2 Sequential Models: Testing the Compositional Hypothesis

