CHAPTER 6: Conclusion — Financial Structure, Immigration, and the Unequal Distribution of Childlessness
Purpose: Synthesize all three empirical chapters, state theoretical contributions, policy implications, and future research agenda.
6.1 The Three-Paper Synthesis
What each paper contributes and how they accumulate:

Paper 1: Parenthood drives debt; the first child is the tipping point
Paper 2: Balance sheet composition, not income, predicts childlessness; racial differences mediated by financial/demographic controls
Paper 3: Nativity composition explains 59% of the Hispanic-White childlessness gap; the nativity effect is mediated through marriage and religion

6.2 The Overarching Argument
The dissertation demonstrates that childlessness in America is shaped by two intersecting structural forces that most research treats separately: the financial structure of households (what they own, owe, and can borrow) and the nativity composition of racial populations (the fertility norms immigrants bring, and how quickly these converge across generations). No single dataset captures both — the SCF has financial depth without nativity, the NSFG has nativity without financial granularity. The methodological contribution is demonstrating what a multi-dataset approach reveals that no single source can.
6.3 Theoretical Contributions

Extension of assimilation theory to fertility outcomes, with explicit test of the mediation pathway through marriage and religion
Financial barriers to family formation as a structural account connecting debt, credit access, and childlessness
The measurement critique: aggregate racial fertility statistics are compositional artifacts

6.4 Policy Implications

For fertility policy: income support alone cannot reverse childlessness driven by educational investment, marriage delay, and secular change; nativity-based buffering of aggregate fertility is temporary and generationally bounded
For financial policy: credit access expansion increases debt prevalence without reducing severity; wage growth and emergency savings are the effective levers
For family support policy: the parenthood debt penalty concentrates at the first child — financial preparation programs should target the transition to parenthood

6.5 Limitations and Future Research

Three-category generational status (requires parental birthplace data or earlier NSFG waves)
Country-of-origin subgroup analysis for Hispanic and AAPI populations (requires pooled multi-wave data)
Longitudinal tracking of debt accumulation around the parenthood transition
Male fertility and paternal financial strain
The AAPI heterogeneity research agenda


